# MediaStudyShelf — Implementation Spec

A local-first course player for video, PDF, and audio lessons. Your folder structure is the content model — no CMS, no import, no database.

**Project site:** mediastudyshelf.com
**License:** GNU Affero General Public License v3.0 (AGPLv3)
**Stack:** Python (FastAPI) backend + React/Vite frontend

---

## 1. Goals & non-goals

**Goals**
- Browse courses organized as `Course → Module → Class`.
- View each class with video and PDF side-by-side (stacked vertically), plus supporting audio and extras.
- Serve everything from a local content folder — adding a lesson means dropping files in a folder.
- Support multiple PDFs per lesson with a selector.
- Stay flexible enough to extend later (metadata, progress tracking, sync), but dumb enough to work today with zero configuration.

**Non-goals (for v1)**
- User accounts, multi-user features, auth.
- Cloud hosting, CDN, streaming transcoding.
- Rich authoring tools inside the app — editing happens in the filesystem.
- Video/PDF time-sync (bookmarked as a future feature, not v1).
- Progress tracking across sessions (the right rail's `✓` on completed lessons in the mockup is aspirational — see open questions).

---

## 2. Content model — filesystem as source of truth

### 2.1 Folder layout

```
/content
  /01-intro-to-systems-thinking          ← Course (slug)
    course.json                          ← optional, see §2.4
    /01-foundations                      ← Module
      /01-what-is-a-system                ← Class (lesson)
        video.mp4
        lesson-notes.pdf
        walkthrough.mp3
      /02-feedback-loops
        video.mp4
        lesson-notes.pdf
        worksheet.pdf
        transcript.pdf
        walkthrough.mp3
        q-and-a.mp3
        resources.zip
      /03-stocks-and-flows
        ...
    /02-modeling
      ...
```

### 2.2 Ordering convention

Folders are **prefixed with two-digit numbers** (`01-`, `02-`, …) for deterministic ordering. The prefix is parsed off for display — users see "What is a system?", not "01 What Is A System".

- Prefix format: `^(\d{2,3})-(.+)$`
- Display name: kebab-case converted to sentence case (`feedback-loops` → `Feedback loops`).
- If a folder has no numeric prefix, it sorts alphabetically **after** all prefixed folders.

### 2.3 File classification — by extension, no metadata required

Files within a class folder are classified by extension:

| Category | Extensions |
|----------|------------|
| Video | `.mp4`, `.webm`, `.mov` |
| PDF / Document | `.pdf` |
| Audio | `.mp3`, `.m4a`, `.wav`, `.ogg` |
| Extras | everything else (`.zip`, `.txt`, `.md`, `.csv`, …) |

**Primary video:** the first video file alphabetically. Multiple videos per lesson is an edge case — if it happens, the others move to Extras.

**Primary PDF (default selection):** resolve in this order, stop at first match:
1. A PDF named `lesson.pdf` or `main.pdf` (case-insensitive).
2. The first PDF alphabetically.

All PDFs remain available in the dropdown selector — "primary" only means "which one opens when the user enters the lesson." The user's active selection is per-session (see §3.5).

**Audio:** all audio files are treated equally. Display name = filename without extension, converted to sentence case. First audio alphabetically is labeled "Walkthrough" only if we can't derive a better name from the filename.

### 2.4 Optional metadata — `course.json`, `module.json`, `class.json`

Metadata is **fully optional**. The filesystem alone produces a valid course. Metadata files at any level override derived defaults.

```json
// course.json (at the course root)
{
  "title": "Intro to Systems Thinking",
  "description": "A foundations course on feedback, stocks, and leverage.",
  "author": "Your Name",
  "cover_image": "cover.jpg"
}

// module.json (in a module folder) — rarely needed
{
  "title": "Foundations"
}

// class.json (in a class folder)
{
  "title": "Feedback loops",
  "primary_pdf": "worksheet.pdf",
  "order": ["video.mp4", "worksheet.pdf", "lesson-notes.pdf", "transcript.pdf"],
  "audio_labels": {
    "walkthrough.mp3": "Walkthrough",
    "q-and-a.mp3": "Q&A session"
  }
}
```

**Rule:** a missing metadata file is not an error. Every field is optional. The walker merges derived defaults with any overrides it finds.

---

## 3. UI specification

The UI is a three-column layout. Widths are fixed for the side rails, main area fills the remaining space.

```
┌──────────┬────────────────────────────────┬──────────┐
│  Course  │          Lesson header         │  Lesson  │
│   nav    ├────────────────────────────────┤   files  │
│  (200px) │                                │ (200px)  │
│          │          Video player          │          │
│          │           (240px tall)         │          │
│          ├────────────────────────────────┤          │
│          │                                │          │
│          │          PDF viewer            │          │
│          │         (fills rest)           │          │
│          │                                │          │
│          ├────────────────────────────────┤          │
│          │     Prev / Next navigation     │          │
└──────────┴────────────────────────────────┴──────────┘
```

### 3.1 Left rail — course navigation (200px wide)

- **Course title** at the top: label `COURSE` (uppercase, tertiary text, 10px, 0.5px letter-spacing), then course name (13px, weight 500).
- Below: a list of modules, each with a section header (`MODULE 1 · FOUNDATIONS`, uppercase, 10px, secondary text) followed by its classes.
- Each class row:
    - 12px status circle on the left:
        - **Completed:** filled success-colored circle with a checkmark (see open question on progress tracking).
        - **Active:** solid info-colored circle, full info-colored row background (`var(--color-background-info)`), info text color, weight 500.
        - **Inactive:** empty circle with a 0.5px border.
    - Class title (12px).
- Spacing between modules: `padding: 12px 6px 4px` on the section header.
- Background: `var(--color-background-secondary)`.
- Right border: 0.5px solid `var(--color-border-tertiary)`.

### 3.2 Main area — lesson header

Padding: `0.75rem 1.125rem`. Bottom border: 0.5px tertiary.

**Left side of header:**
- Breadcrumb: `Module 1 · Foundations` (10px, tertiary text).
- Lesson title: `1.2 Feedback loops` (14px, weight 500).

**Right side of header — view toggle:**
Three small buttons: `Split` | `Video` | `PDF`. Currently active one visually distinct (see button spec). Default: `Split`. These control whether the video+PDF stack both show or one fills the whole main area.

### 3.3 Main area — video pane (top section, ~240px tall in Split view)

- Fixed height: 240px in split view. In "Video" view, expands to fill available height.
- Background: `#0a0a0a` with a subtle diagonal gradient (`linear-gradient(135deg, #1a1a1a 0%, #0a0a0a 100%)`).
- Center: play button (46px circle, 92% white fill, black play-triangle icon).
- Top-left label: `VIDEO` (10px, uppercase, 0.5 letter-spacing, 55% white).
- Bottom bar (9px 14px padding, dark background, 0.5px top border `rgba(255,255,255,0.08)`):
    - Current time (`3:42`), progress bar (3px tall, white at 90% for filled portion, `rgba(255,255,255,0.15)` for track), duration (`12:34`).
    - Time labels: 10px, `rgba(255,255,255,0.7)`.
- Bottom border of the whole pane: 0.5px tertiary (separates from PDF pane).

Use an HTML5 `<video>` element as the actual player. The mockup shows a styled poster state; the real implementation should render native controls or a minimal custom control strip matching this spec.

### 3.4 Main area — PDF pane (bottom section, fills remaining height)

Background: `var(--color-background-secondary)`.

**PDF header bar** (`7px 14px` padding, primary background, bottom 0.5px tertiary):

Contains two groups:

*Left — PDF selector (dropdown):*
- Displayed as a button: `[PDF] lesson-notes.pdf  3 of 3  ▾`
- Padding: `4px 10px`. Background: `var(--color-background-primary)`. Border: 0.5px secondary. Radius: `var(--border-radius-md)`.
- PDF icon: 14×14, 3px radius, `var(--color-background-danger)` bg, `var(--color-text-danger)` text, "PDF" label at 6px weight 500.
- Filename: 11px, weight 500.
- Counter `3 of 3`: 10px, weight 400, tertiary color. **Only shown when there are 2+ PDFs.**
- Chevron: 10px icon, secondary color.
- **If there's only one PDF:** show the same button structure but no chevron, no counter, and disable click. It becomes a static label.

*Open state:* dropdown menu appears below the button, anchored to its left edge. 240px wide. White background, 0.5px secondary border, `var(--border-radius-md)`, subtle shadow (`0 4px 16px rgba(0,0,0,0.08)`), `z-index: 10`.
- Each item (`7px 10px` padding, 5px radius):
    - PDF icon (16×16), filename (11px), metadata (`8 pages · 420 KB`, 9px tertiary).
    - Currently active item: `var(--color-background-info)` background, info text color, trailing checkmark icon on the right.
    - Inactive items: hover-highlighted, cursor pointer.

*Right — PDF viewer controls:*
- Zoom out / zoom level / zoom in: `−` `100%` `+` (10px, secondary).
- Separated by a 0.5px left border: page counter `3 / 8`.

**PDF viewer area:**
- Padding: `14px`.
- Content: rendered PDF page, centered, max-width 340px, aspect ratio matches the actual page. White background, 0.5px tertiary border, 2px radius, `box-shadow: none`.
- Use [PDF.js](https://mozilla.github.io/pdf.js/) for rendering. It's the battle-tested option and the open question about zoom/scroll behavior is answered by the library's defaults.

### 3.5 Right rail — lesson files (200px wide)

- Background: `var(--color-background-secondary)`.
- Left border: 0.5px tertiary.
- Padding: `0.875rem 0.625rem`.

**Header:** `LESSON FILES` (10px uppercase, 0.5 letter-spacing, tertiary), 8px bottom margin.

**Sections** (repeat for Documents, Audio, Extras — omit a section if empty):
- Section label (10px uppercase, 0.3 letter-spacing, secondary), bottom 4px padding.
- File rows:

*Document row* (clickable — activates the PDF in the PDF pane):
```
[PDF icon 22×22]  filename.pdf
                  8 pages · 420 KB
```
Padding `7px 8px`, 4px `border-radius-md`. Icon: `var(--color-background-danger)` bg, red text, "PDF" at 8px weight 500. Filename 11px. Metadata 9px tertiary. Text truncates with ellipsis.

*Audio row:*
```
[▶ circle]  Walkthrough
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━  8:14
```
- Circle play button (22×22): info-bg with info-text if playing, otherwise primary bg with secondary text and a 0.5px tertiary border.
- Filename 11px weight 500.
- Progress bar below: 2px tall, full width, filled portion in info color (or secondary if not yet played).
- Duration label at the end: 9px tertiary.

*Extras row:*
```
[ZIP icon]  resources.zip
            8 files · 2.1 MB
```
- Icon: generic secondary background with secondary text, 0.5px tertiary border. Label = uppercase extension (ZIP, TXT, CSV, …).
- Clicking downloads or opens the file — implementation's choice (see open question).

### 3.6 Footer navigation

Bottom of the main column, above the side rails' content ends. Padding: `9px 1.125rem`, top border 0.5px tertiary.

- Left button: `← 1.1 What is a system?` (11px)
- Right button: `1.3 Stocks & flows →` (11px)
- If first class in the course: no previous button. If last: no next button.
- Navigating wraps across module boundaries — 1.3 → 2.1, not 1.3 → 1.1.

### 3.7 Design tokens

The mockup uses claude.ai's design tokens. For a standalone app, inline these values (extracted from the mockup — adjust for your app's brand if you want):

```css
/* Light mode defaults */
--color-background-primary: #ffffff;
--color-background-secondary: #f4f2ec;
--color-background-tertiary: #eae7dc;
--color-background-info: #e6f1fb;
--color-background-danger: #fcebeb;
--color-background-success: #eaf3de;

--color-text-primary: #1a1a1a;
--color-text-secondary: #5f5e5a;
--color-text-tertiary: #888780;
--color-text-info: #185fa5;
--color-text-danger: #a32d2d;
--color-text-success: #3b6d11;

--color-border-tertiary: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.12);
--color-border-secondary: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);

--border-radius-md: 8px;
--border-radius-lg: 12px;

--font-sans: system-ui, -apple-system, "Segoe UI", sans-serif;
--font-serif: Georgia, "Times New Roman", serif;
```

Dark mode is a future enhancement. If you want it, invert the `--color-background-*` and `--color-text-*` variables and keep everything else the same.

### 3.8 Typography

- **Font sizes:** 10px (micro labels), 11px (body small), 12px (body), 13–14px (lesson/course titles), 15px (page titles).
- **Weights:** 400 (regular) and 500 (bold/emphasis). Never 600+ — too heavy for this UI.
- **Case:** sentence case everywhere except section labels (uppercase with letter-spacing).
- **No bold within sentences.** Bold is for headings and labels only.

---

## 4. Tech stack

### Backend: Python + FastAPI

**Why FastAPI:** native async support (critical for streaming large video files with range requests), automatic OpenAPI docs, Pydantic for typed response models, clean separation between routing and logic. Alternative: Starlette directly if FastAPI feels too heavy — but FastAPI's typing/validation is worth the small overhead for this app.

**Python version:** 3.11 or newer. Use 3.12 if available.

**Core dependencies:**
- `fastapi` — web framework.
- `uvicorn[standard]` — ASGI server (the `[standard]` extras include `uvloop` and `httptools` for performance, plus `watchfiles` for dev reload).
- `pydantic` — response models (comes with FastAPI).
- `pypdf` — PDF page counts. Pure Python, no native dependencies. (`pdfplumber` or `PyMuPDF` are alternatives if you need more; `pypdf` is enough for page counts.)
- `python-magic` — file type detection from content, not just extension (optional but useful for Extras).
- `watchfiles` — dev-mode filesystem watcher for auto-rewalking content directory.

**External binary dependency:**
- `ffprobe` (part of ffmpeg) — for video and audio duration extraction. Must be installed on the host system (`apt install ffmpeg` / `brew install ffmpeg`). The Python side just shells out and parses JSON output. Don't use a Python wrapper library like `ffmpeg-python` — it adds dependencies without saving much code. A simple `subprocess.run(['ffprobe', '-v', 'quiet', '-print_format', 'json', '-show_format', path], capture_output=True)` is enough.

**Dependency management:** use `uv` if you know it (fast, modern), otherwise standard `pyproject.toml` + `pip` is fine. Avoid `poetry` and `pipenv` unless you already prefer them — they add complexity this project doesn't need.

**What the server does:**
- Walks the `/content` directory on startup, builds an in-memory tree, caches it.
- Re-walks on filesystem changes in dev mode (via `watchfiles`), only on startup in prod.
- Serves static media from `/content` at `/media/*` with proper HTTP range-request support. FastAPI's `FileResponse` handles ranges natively, but verify streaming behavior with a long video — range support is critical for video scrubbing and is the one thing most likely to silently break.
- Exposes JSON API at `/api/tree`, `/api/course/{slug}`, `/api/class/{courseSlug}/{moduleSlug}/{classSlug}`.
- CORS configured for localhost dev (frontend runs on a different port via Vite).

### Frontend: React + Vite

**Why React + Vite:** the UI has enough state (current class, view toggle, PDF selector dropdown, video progress, audio players) that vanilla JS would require hand-rolling patterns React gives you for free. Vite is fast, zero-config, and handles dev proxying to the Python backend cleanly.

Alternative: if you prefer Vue or Svelte, either works. Don't pick React if you don't already know it — the UI isn't complex enough to justify learning a new framework.

**Core dependencies:**
- `react`, `react-dom`
- `react-router-dom` — URL-based navigation between classes (enables deep-linking and browser back/forward).
- `pdfjs-dist` — PDF rendering in the PDF pane. This is Mozilla's PDF.js as an npm package.
- No UI library. Everything custom-built per the design tokens in §3.7. The UI is simple enough that component libraries would add more constraint than help.

**Build tool:** Vite. Dev server proxies `/api/*` and `/media/*` requests to the Python backend at `localhost:8000`.

### PDF, video, audio rendering

- **PDF:** PDF.js (`pdfjs-dist`). Render each page to a `<canvas>`. PDF.js's worker loads pages asynchronously; the viewer component should handle the loading state.
- **Video:** native HTML5 `<video>` with `preload="metadata"` and `controls` (custom controls can come later). Source points at `/media/...`.
- **Audio:** native HTML5 `<audio>` with custom UI on top. The mini-players in the right rail show filename, progress bar, and duration.

### Project structure

```
/mediastudyshelf                   ← project root (also the Python project)
  /src
    /mediastudyshelf               ← the importable Python package
      __init__.py
      main.py                      ← FastAPI app entry point
      walker.py                    ← filesystem → tree converter
      models.py                    ← Pydantic response models
      media.py                     ← ffprobe + pypdf helpers
      routes.py                    ← API endpoints
      config.py                    ← settings (content path, dev/prod mode)
  /tests
    test_walker.py
    ...
  /client                          ← React frontend (its own subproject)
    /src
      /components
        CourseNav.jsx              ← left rail
        LessonHeader.jsx
        VideoPane.jsx
        PdfPane.jsx                ← includes dropdown selector
        AssetRail.jsx              ← right rail
        FooterNav.jsx
      /lib
        api.js                     ← fetch helpers, API client
      App.jsx
      main.jsx
      styles.css
    vite.config.js
    package.json
    index.html
  /content                         ← user's course content (gitignored)
  /sample-content                  ← tiny example course for testing
  pyproject.toml                   ← at the project root
  README.md
  SPEC.md
  LICENSE                          ← AGPLv3
  .gitignore
```

**On the layout:** the project root *is* the Python project. `pyproject.toml`, `pip install -e .`, `pytest`, and `uvicorn` all run from `/mediastudyshelf`. The frontend lives inside `/client` as a separate subproject with its own `package.json` and `node_modules`. This reflects reality: Python is the primary project; the frontend is an included asset that gets built and served by the Python server.

**On the `src/` layout:** the Python package lives inside `/src/mediastudyshelf/`, not directly at `/mediastudyshelf/` top-level. This is the recommended modern layout (see [PyPA's guide](https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/discussions/src-layout-vs-flat-layout/)). It prevents accidental imports from the working directory and forces the dev environment to match the installed state — bugs that would only show up after packaging get caught during development.

**On package naming:** the importable Python package is `mediastudyshelf` (not `mediastudyshelf_server`), because the backend is the only Python component — no ambiguity in imports. The PyPI distribution name set in `pyproject.toml` is `mediastudyshelf-server`, which distinguishes the server component from the overall project when discussing releases. In code, imports read clean: `from mediastudyshelf.walker import walk`.

The frontend lives in `/client` with its own dependency management. Python and JavaScript communicate over HTTP. In dev, Vite proxies requests to the Python server; in prod, the Python server serves the built frontend as static files from `/client/dist` (via FastAPI's `StaticFiles` mount).

### Deployment model

**Dev:** run two processes — Python server (`uvicorn mediastudyshelf.main:app --reload`) and Vite dev server (`npm run dev`). Vite proxies to Python.

**Prod:** build the frontend (`npm run build`), Python server mounts the resulting `/client/dist` at `/` and serves everything from one port. Run with `uvicorn mediastudyshelf.main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000`.

**Packaging later:** Docker image with Python + ffmpeg + built frontend baked in is the obvious distribution path, matching how audiobookshelf and immich ship. Out of scope for v1 but keep it in mind — don't do anything that'd make Dockerization painful.

---

## 5. API shape

### `GET /api/tree`
Returns the full course list with minimal info for the navigation.

```json
{
  "courses": [
    {
      "slug": "intro-to-systems-thinking",
      "title": "Intro to Systems Thinking",
      "modules": [
        {
          "slug": "foundations",
          "title": "Foundations",
          "classes": [
            { "slug": "what-is-a-system", "title": "What is a system?", "order": 1 },
            { "slug": "feedback-loops",   "title": "Feedback loops",    "order": 2 },
            { "slug": "stocks-and-flows", "title": "Stocks & flows",    "order": 3 }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

### `GET /api/class/{courseSlug}/{moduleSlug}/{classSlug}`
Returns everything needed to render a class.

```json
{
  "course":  { "slug": "intro-to-systems-thinking", "title": "Intro to Systems Thinking" },
  "module":  { "slug": "foundations", "title": "Foundations", "number": 1 },
  "class":   {
    "slug": "feedback-loops",
    "title": "Feedback loops",
    "number": 2,
    "video": {
      "url": "/media/intro-to-systems-thinking/01-foundations/02-feedback-loops/video.mp4",
      "duration_seconds": 754
    },
    "pdfs": [
      {
        "filename": "lesson-notes.pdf",
        "url": "/media/.../lesson-notes.pdf",
        "pages": 8,
        "size_bytes": 430080,
        "is_primary": true
      },
      {
        "filename": "worksheet.pdf",
        "url": "/media/.../worksheet.pdf",
        "pages": 2,
        "size_bytes": 184320,
        "is_primary": false
      }
    ],
    "audio": [
      {
        "filename": "walkthrough.mp3",
        "label": "Walkthrough",
        "url": "/media/.../walkthrough.mp3",
        "duration_seconds": 1100
      }
    ],
    "extras": [
      {
        "filename": "resources.zip",
        "url": "/media/.../resources.zip",
        "size_bytes": 2202009
      }
    ]
  },
  "nav": {
    "prev": { "course": "...", "module": "foundations", "class": "what-is-a-system", "title": "What is a system?" },
    "next": { "course": "...", "module": "foundations", "class": "stocks-and-flows", "title": "Stocks & flows" }
  }
}
```

**PDF page counts and media durations:** derive server-side at walk time. Use `pypdf` for page counts; use `ffprobe` (shelled out via `subprocess`) for video and audio durations. Cache results in memory — these don't need to be re-read on every request. In dev, the filesystem watcher invalidates the cache for changed paths; in prod, the cache lives for the lifetime of the process.

---

## 6. Implementation order

Suggested sequence, each step verifiable before moving on. The first few steps are backend-only — don't start on the UI until the API is solid.

1. **Project scaffold.** At the project root, create `pyproject.toml` and `/src/mediastudyshelf/` with a minimal FastAPI app in `main.py` that responds to `GET /health`. Install editable: `pip install -e .[dev]` from the project root. Confirm `uvicorn mediastudyshelf.main:app --reload` runs.
2. **Content walker.** Walk a sample `/sample-content` folder, build the tree as plain Python dataclasses or dicts, print it. No API yet — run it as a CLI: `python -m mediastudyshelf.walker ./sample-content`.
3. **`/api/tree` endpoint.** Wire the walker into FastAPI. Return Pydantic-modeled JSON. Test with `curl http://localhost:8000/api/tree`.
4. **Static media serving.** Mount `/content` at `/media/*` using FastAPI's `StaticFiles`. Verify a `curl -I` on a video URL returns `Accept-Ranges: bytes`. Verify range requests work with `curl -H "Range: bytes=0-1023"`.
5. **Enrich the walker.** Add `pypdf` for page counts, `ffprobe` for video and audio durations. Cache results keyed by file path + mtime.
6. **`/api/class/...` endpoint.** Returns the full class payload per §5. Include `prev`/`next` navigation resolution.
7. **Dev-mode filesystem watcher.** Using `watchfiles`, invalidate cached tree entries when files change under `/content`. Only enabled when `--reload` is set or via env var.
8. **Client scaffold.** Vite + React project in `/client`. Configure dev proxy to forward `/api/*` and `/media/*` to `localhost:8000`. Base three-column layout with hardcoded content first, then wire up to the API.
9. **Left rail.** Course nav, module sections, class rows with active state. Use `react-router-dom` for URL-based class selection (`/course/{courseSlug}/{moduleSlug}/{classSlug}`).
10. **Video pane.** Native `<video>` pointing at `/media/...`. Confirm scrubbing works end-to-end — this tests range-request handling.
11. **PDF pane.** PDF.js rendering via `pdfjs-dist`, page navigation, zoom controls.
12. **PDF selector dropdown.** Multi-PDF lessons, active state, counter logic (hidden when only one PDF).
13. **Right rail.** Documents, audio (with inline mini-players), extras.
14. **Footer navigation.** Prev/next with cross-module wrapping.
15. **View toggle.** Split / Video only / PDF only.
16. **Prod build path.** Vite builds to `/client/dist`, FastAPI serves it as static files when a `SERVE_FRONTEND=1` env var is set. Single-command prod deployment.
17. **Polish.** Loading states, empty states (lesson with no video, lesson with no PDFs), error handling for missing files, 404 pages.

---

## 7. Open questions (decide before or during implementation)

These came up during design but don't block starting. Worth answering before polishing.

**Progress tracking.** The left rail shows completed lessons with a checkmark (`1.1 What is a system? ✓`). Where does this state live?
- *Option A — off for v1.* All lessons show empty circles. Remove the completed state from the mockup.
- *Option B — localStorage.* Track "viewed" status per class. Simple, per-browser, good enough for a personal app.
- *Option C — a `progress.json` in the content folder.* Portable across machines if you sync the content folder.

Recommendation: **B** for v1. Upgrade to C if you end up using this on multiple machines.

**PDF state persistence per class.** If I'm on lesson 1.2 viewing `transcript.pdf`, then navigate to 1.3 and back — does 1.2 remember transcript, or reset to the primary PDF?
- Recommendation: **reset to primary.** Simpler mental model, avoids surprise. Use a URL query param (`?pdf=transcript.pdf`) if you want deep-linking.

**Split divider.** Should the video/PDF split be draggable (user drags the boundary to favor one pane)?
- Recommendation: **not in v1.** Fixed 240px video height. Add if it bugs you.

**Extras click behavior.** Does clicking `resources.zip` download it or open in a new tab?
- Recommendation: **download** for archives, **open in new tab** for everything else. Or: always download, with a "copy link" option.

**Video + PDF sync.** Timestamps in the video that auto-flip PDF pages.
- Recommendation: **out of scope for v1.** If you add it later, it's a `class.json` field: `"pdf_sync": [{ "time": 180, "pdf": "lesson-notes.pdf", "page": 3 }]`.

**Watcher behavior.** Does the server live-reload when files change in `/content`?
- Recommendation: **yes in dev** (via `watchfiles`), **no in prod** (walk on startup only). Makes adding a new lesson feel instant during development. Gate behind an env var (`WATCH_CONTENT=1`) or the `--reload` flag so prod deploys don't waste cycles watching.

**Windows path handling.** If you're on Windows, the walker needs to handle backslashes and the URL layer needs to always use forward slashes.

---

## 8. Getting started

Once Claude Code picks this up:

1. Confirm the content model with a sample folder under `/sample-content`. Even one course with one module and two classes is enough to validate the walker.
2. Scaffold the Python package at `/src/mediastudyshelf/` with FastAPI and get `uvicorn mediastudyshelf.main:app --reload` serving `GET /health`.
3. Build the walker as a standalone module, then add a CLI entrypoint so you can test it in isolation: `python -m mediastudyshelf.walker ./sample-content` should print the tree.
4. Only once `/api/tree` returns clean JSON and static media serves with range support, start on the frontend.

The UI mockup this spec is based on uses claude.ai's design system — the CSS tokens in §3.7 are a good starting approximation, but you'll want to iterate on spacing and color once you see it in your own browser. Don't treat the pixel values as gospel; treat the layout hierarchy and component behavior as the contract.

### Minimal `pyproject.toml` starting point

```toml
[project]
name = "mediastudyshelf-server"
version = "0.1.0"
description = "Local-first course player for video, PDF, and audio lessons"
readme = "README.md"
license = { text = "AGPL-3.0-or-later" }
requires-python = ">=3.11"
dependencies = [
  "fastapi>=0.110",
  "uvicorn[standard]>=0.27",
  "pypdf>=4.0",
  "watchfiles>=0.21",
]

[project.optional-dependencies]
dev = [
  "pytest>=8.0",
  "httpx>=0.27",   # for FastAPI TestClient
  "ruff>=0.3",
]

[project.scripts]
# CLI entrypoint for testing the walker in isolation:
# `mediastudyshelf-walker ./sample-content`
mediastudyshelf-walker = "mediastudyshelf.walker:main"

[build-system]
requires = ["setuptools>=68"]
build-backend = "setuptools.build_meta"

[tool.setuptools.packages.find]
where = ["src"]

[tool.ruff]
line-length = 100
target-version = "py311"

[tool.pytest.ini_options]
testpaths = ["tests"]
```

The `[tool.setuptools.packages.find]` section tells setuptools that packages live under `src/`. This is what makes the `src/` layout work — without it, setuptools would look for the package at the project root and fail to find it.

**On the choice of `pyproject.toml` over `setup.py`:** `pyproject.toml` is the modern standard (PEP 621, widely adopted since 2021) and is what all current Python tooling expects. `setup.py` is legacy — it still works but it scatters configuration across multiple files, runs arbitrary code at install time, and is explicitly discouraged by setuptools' own documentation for new projects. Use pyproject.

### Runtime prerequisites

- **Python 3.11+**
- **ffmpeg** installed on the host (provides `ffprobe`). The app will fail loudly at startup if `ffprobe` isn't on the `PATH`.
- **Node.js 20+** for the frontend build.

